 It is so much better to be single today and trust God and look for the characteristics he said,

446
00:31:16,000 --> 00:31:23,000
 to be single and lonely today than to be married and lonely someday.

447
00:31:23,000 --> 00:31:31,000
 That loneliness is a far greater depth, and you probably don't believe me,

448
00:31:31,000 --> 00:31:37,000
 but I've been teaching on dating on this stage and at this place for 12 years,

449
00:31:37,000 --> 00:31:46,000
 and I have seen nothing destroy the hearts and lives of people like their toxic dating relationships,

450
00:31:46,000 --> 00:31:49,000
 the compromises that they've made.

451
00:31:49,000 --> 00:31:53,000
 And I just don't want that for you.

452
00:31:53,000 --> 00:31:57,000
 And you've got to decide, "Man, am I looking for this relationship to fill?

453
00:31:57,000 --> 00:32:02,000
 I'm looking for something to fill a hole in me that maybe they can't fill."

454
00:32:02,000 --> 00:32:04,000
 Because they can't.

455
00:32:04,000 --> 00:32:07,000
 You're dating dehydrated.

456
00:32:07,000 --> 00:32:12,000
 You want to approach dating as a whole person, W-H-O-L-E, "I'm a whole person.

457
00:32:12,000 --> 00:32:15,000
 I'm complete in Christ. If they don't complete me, I'm complete in Christ."

458
00:32:15,000 --> 00:32:19,000
 Not approach dating as a whole, H-O-L-E, like, "I got holes in my life,

459
00:32:19,000 --> 00:32:23,000
 and I'm looking for you to plug and you to fill them."

460
00:32:23,000 --> 00:32:25,000
 Because they won't be able to.

461
00:32:25,000 --> 00:32:28,000
 This woman tried and tried and tried and tried.

462
00:32:28,000 --> 00:32:31,000
 She had five marriages.

463
00:32:31,000 --> 00:32:34,000
 Some of us are like, "I just want one, God. I just want one marriage."

464
00:32:34,000 --> 00:32:38,000
 She got five, and it didn't work.

465
00:32:38,000 --> 00:32:41,000
 I was on Instagram, and I did a poll yesterday and asked,

466
00:32:41,000 --> 00:32:44,000
 "Hey, what are some examples of being relationally thirsty?"

467
00:32:44,000 --> 00:32:46,000
 And y'all are crazy, man.

468
00:32:46,000 --> 00:32:49,000
 So here's some of the examples and answers.

469
00:32:49,000 --> 00:32:53,000
 [Laughter]

470
00:32:53,000 --> 00:32:55,000
 They dress like a harlot.

471
00:32:55,000 --> 00:32:59,000
 They hop from one relationship to the next to the next.

472
00:32:59,000 --> 00:33:03,000
 They only text you and slide into your DMs at 3 a.m.

473
00:33:03,000 --> 00:33:06,000
 They're on every dating app imaginable.

474
00:33:06,000 --> 00:33:10,000
 They have the Snapchat handle in their Instagram bio.

475
00:33:10,000 --> 00:33:14,000
 Hard pass.

476
00:33:14,000 --> 00:33:19,000
 Man, it's probably time for everybody to just retire Snapchat.

477
00:33:19,000 --> 00:33:22,000
 [Applause]

478
00:33:22,000 --> 00:33:25,000
 Wow.

479
00:33:25,000 --> 00:33:27,000
 You're welcome, TikTok.

480
00:33:27,000 --> 00:33:30,000
 They'll take anyone. They wear revealing clothes.

481
00:33:30,000 --> 00:33:35,000
 They continuously jump from one relationship to the next.

482
00:33:35,000 --> 00:33:39,000
 They're always talking about how they just wish that they were in a relationship.

483
00:33:39,000 --> 00:33:41,000
 It's all they ever post on Instagram about.

484
00:33:41,000 --> 00:33:44,000
 They're serially dating.

485
00:33:44,000 --> 00:33:49,000
 They lower their standards to address their loneliness.

486
00:33:49,000 --> 00:33:56,000
 They're grasping for attention and thirst traps.

487
00:33:56,000 --> 00:34:03,000
 Now, those may not be the ways that you would say, "I'm dating dehydrated,"

488
00:34:03,000 --> 00:34:05,000
 but I would ask you the question, to be honest with yourself,

489
00:34:05,000 --> 00:34:08,000
 like, "Are you dating from a healthy, strong relationship in Christ?"

490
00:34:08,000 --> 00:34:10,000
 And some of you are. Some of you should date.

491
00:34:10,000 --> 00:34:11,000
 And you're in a great place with Christ.

492
00:34:11,000 --> 00:34:13,000
 And you're single. And I'm so proud of you.

493
00:34:13,000 --> 00:34:15,000
 And keep going.

494
00:34:15,000 --> 00:34:18,000
 But some of you, you're dating dehydrated.

495
00:34:18,000 --> 00:34:22,000
 And that person can't quench your thirst.

496
00:34:22,000 --> 00:34:26,000
 You're asking them to do what only Jesus can, like salt water.

497
00:34:26,000 --> 00:34:29,000
 There's no amount of salt water that can quench your thirst.

498
00:34:29,000 --> 00:34:32,000
 And if I approach salt water and want it to quench my thirst,

499
00:34:32,000 --> 00:34:34,000
 I'm asking it to do something it cannot do.

500
00:34:34,000 --> 00:34:38,000
 And you dating someone, expecting them to fill the hole that only Jesus can,

501
00:34:38,000 --> 00:34:41,000
 is asking them to do something they cannot do.

502
00:34:41,000 --> 00:34:44,000
 And I have seen this creep in, even in Christian circles,

503
00:34:44,000 --> 00:34:49,000
 where people, they don't even fully realize that they're looking for this person

504
00:34:49,000 --> 00:34:53,000
 to fill a hole, and then they get married, and they don't fill that hole,

505
00:34:53,000 --> 00:34:57,000
 and they go, "Maybe I married the wrong person."

506
00:34:57,000 --> 00:35:01,000
 In fact, almost every affair that I've ever been a part of,

507
00:35:01,000 --> 00:35:04,000
 counseled, shepherded, cared for people that are walking through,

508
00:35:04,000 --> 00:35:06,000
 happens the exact same way.

509
00:35:06,000 --> 00:35:10,000
 In fact, an affair happens by somebody in this room, and I hope it never does.

510
00:35:10,000 --> 00:35:12,000
 But if it does, let me just tell you the offense.

511
00:35:12,000 --> 00:35:14,000
 It happens almost the exact same way every time.

512
00:35:14,000 --> 00:35:16,000
 You ready?

513
00:35:16,000 --> 00:35:18,000
 A couple gets married. They're in love.

514
00:35:18,000 --> 00:35:20,000
 Things are going well. They took the vows.

515
00:35:20,000 --> 00:35:22,000
 They're together.

516
00:35:22,000 --> 00:35:24,000
 Bring in some little kids along the way.

517
00:35:24,000 --> 00:35:26,000
 They're journeying through life. Things are hard.

518
00:35:26,000 --> 00:35:28,000
 Bodies are changing. Job's hard.

519
00:35:28,000 --> 00:35:34,000
 All of a sudden, they don't have as much time to prioritize just the two of them.

520
00:35:34,000 --> 00:35:37,000
 He's over here at work all day long, eight hours a day.

521
00:35:37,000 --> 00:35:39,000
 And you know what happens at work?

522
00:35:39,000 --> 00:35:41,000
 He's spending a lot of time around people and some coworkers,

523
00:35:41,000 --> 00:35:43,000
 some of the opposite sex, and he's thriving.

524
00:35:43,000 --> 00:35:45,000
 He's shining. He's got his best.

525
00:35:45,000 --> 00:35:47,000
 He's had a cup of coffee. He's sharp. He's ready.

526
00:35:47,000 --> 00:35:49,000
 Unlike at night where he goes home, and he's changing diapers,

527
00:35:49,000 --> 00:35:51,000
 and he's going through all those challenges at work,

528
00:35:51,000 --> 00:35:53,000
 he's around people that are seeing him thrive

529
00:35:53,000 --> 00:35:56,000
 or seeing him use his gifts and seeing him what he's good at creating,

530
00:35:56,000 --> 00:35:58,000
 designing, making.

531
00:35:58,000 --> 00:36:01,000
 And some of the opposite sex begins to connect with him and go,

532
00:36:01,000 --> 00:36:03,000
 "Man, you're so great at that."

533
00:36:03,000 --> 00:36:07,000
 And it starts with an emotional connection.

534
00:36:07,000 --> 00:36:09,000
 And while that's happening,

535
00:36:09,000 --> 00:36:14,000
 and the flirting is happening back and forth,

536
00:36:14,000 --> 00:36:17,000
 all of a sudden, they begin to spend more time together one-on-one.

537
00:36:17,000 --> 00:36:19,000
 And maybe it's at lunch, and it's not a big deal.

538
00:36:19,000 --> 00:36:21,000
 And all the while, just at home, things are challenging,

539
00:36:21,000 --> 00:36:25,000
 and life is hard, and it's stressful, and schedules are busy.

540
00:36:25,000 --> 00:36:27,000
 But at work, it's like, "Man, we've got wide-open spaces,

541
00:36:27,000 --> 00:36:32,000
 and she appreciates me. She knows my gifts."

542
00:36:32,000 --> 00:36:34,000
 And you begin to confide in one another.

543
00:36:34,000 --> 00:36:39,000
 I mean, I've seen it happen more times than I could count.

544
00:36:39,000 --> 00:36:41,000
 And eventually, a physical line is crossed.

545
00:36:41,000 --> 00:36:43,000
 And you know what the mindset of this person

546
00:36:43,000 --> 00:36:45,000
 who's crossing that boundary the whole time is?

547
00:36:45,000 --> 00:36:49,000
 "I think I married the wrong person."

548
00:36:49,000 --> 00:36:51,000
 The majority of affairs happen at work.

549
00:36:51,000 --> 00:36:53,000
 And they don't happen because people are going like,

550
00:36:53,000 --> 00:36:55,000
 "You know what? I'm just going to ruin everything in my life today."

551
00:36:55,000 --> 00:36:57,000
 They happen because they go,

552
00:36:57,000 --> 00:37:01,000
 "Oh, I think I married the wrong person,

553
00:37:01,000 --> 00:37:04,000
 and I don't want to be unhappy."

554
00:37:04,000 --> 00:37:08,000
 And they're delusional. They're dehydrated.

555
00:37:08,000 --> 00:37:10,000
 They think, "If I could just get with the right person,

556
00:37:10,000 --> 00:37:13,000
 everything would be fine.

557
00:37:13,000 --> 00:37:15,000
 And I must have married the wrong one."

558
00:37:15,000 --> 00:37:17,000
 You have never married--

559
00:37:17,000 --> 00:37:22,000
 no one in history has ever married the wrong person

560
00:37:22,000 --> 00:37:25,000
 because they're who you're married to.

561
00:37:25,000 --> 00:37:28,000
 But if you chase and you operate looking for none to fill,

562
00:37:28,000 --> 00:37:31,000
 that's the storyline of how it always happens.

563
00:37:31,000 --> 00:37:34,000
 So you want to be someone who dates complete in Christ

564
00:37:34,000 --> 00:37:36,000
 and only dates people who are complete in Christ.

565
00:37:36,000 --> 00:37:38,000
 And finally, the last one.

566
00:37:38,000 --> 00:37:43,000
 Dating--when you are dating damaged--

567
00:37:43,000 --> 00:37:45,000
 now, I want to be really careful and be very specific,

568
00:37:45,000 --> 00:37:48,000
 because I know already people feel like damaged goods

569
00:37:48,000 --> 00:37:51,000
 in this talk and just in general.

570
00:37:51,000 --> 00:37:55,000
 By damaged, all of us in life experience hurts, trauma,

571
00:37:55,000 --> 00:37:58,000
 abuse to varying degrees,

572
00:37:58,000 --> 00:38:02,000
 but painful moments in our story.

573
00:38:02,000 --> 00:38:05,000
 The absence of a father or the abandonment of a parent

574
00:38:05,000 --> 00:38:08,000
 or something that hurts inside of your life,

575
00:38:08,000 --> 00:38:10,000
 and you have the responsibility and I have the responsibility.

576
00:38:10,000 --> 00:38:12,000
 It wasn't your fault that that happened,

577
00:38:12,000 --> 00:38:16,000
 but it is now your responsibility to heal from it

578
00:38:16,000 --> 00:38:20,000
 and not date from a damaged place.

579
00:38:20,000 --> 00:38:22,000
 But I've got the decision and you have got the decision

580
00:38:22,000 --> 00:38:24,000
 and the responsibility to decide,

581
00:38:24,000 --> 00:38:26,000
 "I'm going to heal from the hurt and the harm

582
00:38:26,000 --> 00:38:28,000
 that happened to me."

583
00:38:28,000 --> 00:38:31,000
 Because if you don't heal from hurts, from cuts,

584
00:38:31,000 --> 00:38:33,000
 from things that will happen to you,

585
00:38:33,000 --> 00:38:35,000
 you are going to bleed out on people

586
00:38:35,000 --> 00:38:38,000
 who never hurt you and never cut you.

587
00:38:38,000 --> 00:38:40,000
 We say that again.

588
00:38:40,000 --> 00:38:43,000
 If you don't heal from what happened to you,

589
00:38:43,000 --> 00:38:46,000
 you are going to bleed out in life

590
00:38:46,000 --> 00:38:49,000
 on people, relationships, spouses, dating,

591
00:38:49,000 --> 00:38:52,000
 on people who never cut you.

592
00:38:52,000 --> 00:38:55,000
 But you can decide, "Man, I'm going to heal."

593
00:38:55,000 --> 00:38:58,000
 How do you heal from past trauma and past abuse?

594
00:38:58,000 --> 00:39:00,000
 We did an entire series called "Anti-Suppressants"

595
00:39:00,000 --> 00:39:01,000
 on working through this stuff.

596
00:39:01,000 --> 00:39:03,000
 But one of the things you've got to decide is,

597
00:39:03,000 --> 00:39:05,000
 "I'm going to forgive.

598
00:39:05,000 --> 00:39:10,000
 I'm going to choose to forgive people that have hurt me.

599
00:39:10,000 --> 00:39:13,000
 I'm not going to carry this anymore.

600
00:39:13,000 --> 00:39:15,000
 I'm not going to let this person

601
00:39:15,000 --> 00:39:17,000
 have any more control in my life.

602
00:39:17,000 --> 00:39:19,000
 I'm going to forgive them."

603
00:39:19,000 --> 00:39:21,000
 And again, I'd encourage you to go listen to that message

604
00:39:21,000 --> 00:39:24,000
 on releasing that debt and entrusting that to God,

605
00:39:24,000 --> 00:39:27,000
 "Anti-Suppressants" from earlier this summer.

606
00:39:27,000 --> 00:39:29,000
 But I'm going to choose to forgive them.

607
00:39:29,000 --> 00:39:30,000
 Colossians chapter 3 says,

608
00:39:30,000 --> 00:39:33,000
 "We are to forgive one another if you have any grievance,

609
00:39:33,000 --> 00:39:36,000
 just like God in Christ forgave you."

610
00:39:36,000 --> 00:39:38,000
 Anytime I'm doing a wedding of two individuals,

611
00:39:38,000 --> 00:39:41,000
 I ask a series of questions and meeting with them

612
00:39:41,000 --> 00:39:43,000
 and just getting to know them

613
00:39:43,000 --> 00:39:45,000
 and spend time with them before we do the wedding.

614
00:39:45,000 --> 00:39:47,000
 And I ask this question every time,

615
00:39:47,000 --> 00:39:51,000
 "Is there anyone in your life you have not forgiven?"

616
00:39:51,000 --> 00:39:52,000
 And they'll think and they'll go through,

617
00:39:52,000 --> 00:39:55,000
 and sometimes it's, "No, not that I can think of."

618
00:39:55,000 --> 00:40:01,000
 And other times it's, "My dad, my sister,

619
00:40:01,000 --> 00:40:07,000
 my brother, grandparent."

620
00:40:07,000 --> 00:40:13,000
 And I, as tenderly as I can say,

621
00:40:13,000 --> 00:40:18,000
 "I cannot do your wedding until you forgive them."

622
00:40:18,000 --> 00:40:22,000
 And that's not to be harsh or to be hurtful.

623
00:40:22,000 --> 00:40:27,000
 It's 'cause Jesus commands us to in Scripture.

624
00:40:27,000 --> 00:40:30,000
 And if I'm going to stand there and say,

625
00:40:30,000 --> 00:40:32,000
 "By the authority vested in me,

626
00:40:32,000 --> 00:40:35,000
 according to God Almighty,"

627
00:40:35,000 --> 00:40:37,000
 pronounce you man and wife,

628
00:40:37,000 --> 00:40:39,000
 I can't with integrity say,

629
00:40:39,000 --> 00:40:41,000
 "I am joining two people together,"

630
00:40:41,000 --> 00:40:43,000
 and one of them is saying,

631
00:40:43,000 --> 00:40:47,000
 "I carry around hurts and resentment and bitterness."

632
00:40:47,000 --> 00:40:50,000
 Because you two coming together in marriage,

633
00:40:50,000 --> 00:40:52,000
 you've already shown that, "Hey, when I get hurt,

634
00:40:52,000 --> 00:40:53,000
 I'm going to pick this up and I'm going to carry it

635
00:40:53,000 --> 00:40:54,000
 and I'm going to hold onto it."

636
00:40:54,000 --> 00:40:56,000
 There's a level of which, "Man, if you hurt me,

637
00:40:56,000 --> 00:40:57,000
 I'm carrying this with me."

638
00:40:57,000 --> 00:40:59,000
 What happens in marriage is you have

639
00:40:59,000 --> 00:41:02,000
 the most intimate, deep relationship that possibly exists.

640
00:41:02,000 --> 00:41:04,000
 And the greater the depth of intimacy,

641
00:41:04,000 --> 00:41:07,000
 the greater the depth and potential for pain.

642
00:41:07,000 --> 00:41:09,000
 And you're going to have these two people come together,

643
00:41:09,000 --> 00:41:10,000
 and one of them has already said,

644
00:41:10,000 --> 00:41:11,000
 "When I get hurt, I hold onto resentment."

645
00:41:11,000 --> 00:41:13,000
 So inside of that marriage, what are they going to do?

646
00:41:13,000 --> 00:41:17,000
 When they get hurt, they're going to hold onto that resentment.

647
00:41:17,000 --> 00:41:21,000
 And marriage is two people choosing to forgive one another

648
00:41:21,000 --> 00:41:24,000
 after deeply hurting one another,

649
00:41:24,000 --> 00:41:28,000
 unintentionally or intentionally.

650
00:41:28,000 --> 00:41:30,000
 Billy Graham was asked, "What makes a good marriage?"

651
00:41:30,000 --> 00:41:35,000
 And he said, "Two great forgivers."

652
00:41:35,000 --> 00:41:38,000
 Is there anyone that you need to forgive?

653
00:41:38,000 --> 00:41:40,000
 Maybe one of the greatest gifts you can give your spouse

654
00:41:40,000 --> 00:41:43,000
 is saying, "Man, I have worked through and healed

655
00:41:43,000 --> 00:41:47,000
 a lot of painful things, and it may take time,

656
00:41:47,000 --> 00:41:50,000
 but I can say, 'Man, I've forgiven

657
00:41:50,000 --> 00:41:53,000
 all that have harmed and hurt me.'"

658
00:41:53,000 --> 00:41:57,000
 Another way to begin to heal is to deal with toxic habits,

659
00:41:57,000 --> 00:41:59,000
 that eating disorder.

660
00:41:59,000 --> 00:42:02,000
 If there's something you need to confess

661
00:42:02,000 --> 00:42:07,000
 to your community group, a pornography addiction,

662
00:42:07,000 --> 00:42:15,000
 that is feeding and fueling lies as it relates to sexuality,

663
00:42:15,000 --> 00:42:19,000
 a spending problem, that you've got multiple credit cards

664
00:42:19,000 --> 00:42:21,000
 in multiple different directions,

665
00:42:21,000 --> 00:42:23,000
 and you've got a lease on a Range Rover outside,

666
00:42:23,000 --> 00:42:28,000
 and you're way over the top in terms of debt.

667
00:42:28,000 --> 00:42:30,000
 There's a gambling problem.

668
00:42:30,000 --> 00:42:34,000
 Maybe you're coping with just alcohol,

669
00:42:34,000 --> 00:42:38,000
 weed, nicotine, video games.

670
00:42:38,000 --> 00:42:42,000
 That you would deal with those toxic habits now,

671
00:42:42,000 --> 00:42:44,000
 because marriage, like I said, it doesn't make those go away.

672
00:42:44,000 --> 00:42:47,000
 It magnifies them.

673
00:42:47,000 --> 00:42:51,000
 You're putting pressure on it.

674
00:42:51,000 --> 00:42:54,000
 Whatever you're carrying, you can give the gift to your spouse

675
00:42:54,000 --> 00:42:56,000
 of saying, "I'm going to choose in this season to work on that,

676
00:42:56,000 --> 00:42:58,000
 work through that."

677
00:42:58,000 --> 00:43:01,000
 When you go on your honeymoon, you're going to bring luggage with you.

678
00:43:01,000 --> 00:43:05,000
 You want the luggage and baggage you bring

679
00:43:05,000 --> 00:43:09,000
 to be in physical luggage,

680
00:43:09,000 --> 00:43:12,000
 not baggage that you're still carrying.

681
00:43:12,000 --> 00:43:15,000
 Or you want to minimize it as best that you can.

682
00:43:15,000 --> 00:43:22,000
 And that is a gift to your future wife or your future husband.

683
00:43:22,000 --> 00:43:25,000
 And then spend this season prioritizing Jesus.

684
00:43:25,000 --> 00:43:27,000
 Maybe you need to go through REGEN, which is a recovery ministry

685
00:43:27,000 --> 00:43:30,000
 and dealing with different destructive hurts, habits,

686
00:43:30,000 --> 00:43:34,000
 and hangups on Monday nights here at 6 o'clock, 6.30.

687
00:43:34,000 --> 00:43:36,000
 Prioritize pursuing Jesus.

688
00:43:36,000 --> 00:43:39,000
 Paul said in 1 Corinthians 7, "Use this season right now,

689
00:43:39,000 --> 00:43:41,000
 if you're single, to strengthen and solidify

690
00:43:41,000 --> 00:43:43,000
 an undistracted devotion to the Lord."

691
00:43:43,000 --> 00:43:45,000
 My wife and I, we dated for a year,

692
00:43:45,000 --> 00:43:47,000
 and then we broke up for almost two years.

693
00:43:47,000 --> 00:43:49,000
 And there was no plan to get back together.

